Miami-Dade County COVID-19 Trajectory

Miami-Dade County COVID-19 Trajectory

Roy Williams, Gabriel J. Odom, Zoran Bursac, and Mary Jo Trepka

07 July 2020

Introduction

Public understanding of science is critical in times of crisis. The following analysis was conducted to examine the trajectory of COVID-19 in Miami-Dade County. For phased reopening, the White House has set guidelines for local municipalities in their “Opening Up American Again” report. In the report, it is highly suggested that:

  1. Local areas show a downward trajectory in the number of positive cases as a percent of total tests over a two-week period, and
  2. Local hospitals have capacity to handle all patients without crisis care.

The analysis begins by looking at the number of new positive cases each day and the number of total tests performed each day. The figures are presented together because as there is more testing, there are likely to be more positive test results. Therefore, the proportion of positive cases is also calculated. Given either a flat or increasing number of tests performed, the proportion of positive cases is the key metric to be used when looking at epidemic trajectory. It is recommended that this proportion not exceed 5%.

Finally, to ensure hospitals can meet demand without crisis care, the COVID-19 positive hospitalization census, COVID-19 positive ICU census, and COVID-19 positive ventilation census is plotted over time. Census refers to the number of COVID-19 positive patients in the hospital, ICU, and on ventilators, respectively, on a given day.

The data above show for each day since April 2: the number of positive COVID-19 tests, the number of negative COVID-19 tests, and the proportion of positive COVID-19 tests to total COVID-19 tests.

Total COVID-19 Tests by Day

We see the following pattern for the count of total tests over the past two months (shown on a log scale):

The average number of COVID-19 tests performed each day has increased from about 2,000 in early April to just under 10,000 in late-June. On average, from 20 March until 06 July, there was an increase of approximately 67 addition tests performed each day over the previous day. This data is presented on a log scale.

Positive COVID-19 Tests by Day

We see the following pattern for the count of positive tests over the past two months:

There was a general decrease in the number of new positive test results from early April until around May 18th, the day Miami-Dade County reopened. Afterwards, this trend flattened out and then increased. Over the past two weeks, there has been an average increase of 103 new additional positive cases each day. This is compared with 125 new additional positive cases each day from the previous analysis. A high of 2444 for new positive cases was obtained on July 3rd.

Positive COVID-19 Tests within the Past Two Weeks

In addition to the overall trend of positive COVID-19 tests shown above, we also show an enhanced view of the last two weeks, highlighting the stark increase in positive cases during this period of time.

Proportion of Positive Cases within Past Two Weeks

The proportion of positive COVID-19 tests for the past two weeks is:

During the 14-day period from 22 June to 06 July, there was a increase in the proportion of positive COVID-19 cases reported in Miami-Dade County. During this time, there was an average increase of 0.4% per day for new positive cases. Given a flat or increasing number of tests performed, the proportion of positive tests obtained is the key metric for examining COVID-19 trajectory. The percentage of positive test results obtained has exceeded the 5% positive threshold recommended by the World Health Organization (WHO) for reopening.

Proportion of Positive COVID-19 Tests by Day

These are the proportions of positive COVID-19 tests for the since the start of April:

Overall, the proportion of positive test results out of all tests decreased significantly from over 20% in April to 5% on May 18th, the date Miami-Dade County reopened. After reopening, the proportion of positive tests has increased steadily, reaching the current current proportion of over 20%. This number is function of test availability and the population being tested. Given a flat or increasing number of tests performed, an increase in the proportion of positive tests obtained points to evidence of increased COVID-19 community spread in Miami-Dade county.

The data above is COVID-19 hospital census data in Miami-Dade County for all dates with available data since April 2. These columns are: the number of patients hospitalized with COVID-19 (Hospitalized), the number of patients in intensive care with COVID-19 (ICU), the number of patients in intensive care with COVID-19 who are also on ventilators (Ventilated), the number of patients positive for COVID-19 that were admitted the previous day (AdmitPrevDay), the number of patients recovered from COVID-19 that were discharged the previous day (DischPrevDay), and the net admission of patients positive for COVID-19 the previous day (DeltaAdmit; a negative value means more recovered patients were discharged than sick patients admitted). There is a data error for the count ventilated on the 4th of June. We removed this point from the data before estimating the models shown below.

Hospital COVID-19 Census

We now show a census plot of hospitalizations, patients in ICU, and those in ICU on ventilators (shown on a log scale):

Overall, since mid-April, the number of COVID-19 positive patients in Miami-Dade County hospitals remained constant at around 700 people in hospitals until early June. The COVID-19 ICU census decreased from its reported peak of 285 on April 17th to around 100 as of June 6th. Overall, the number of COVID-19 patients on ventilators has decreased from its highest point of 192 ventilated on April 22nd to around 60 on June 6th. However, the observed decreasing trends for ICU census and ventilation census have reversed over the past four weeks and begun to increase for ICU census and ventilation census, respectively. Additionally, county hospitalizations have begun to increase as well. On July 6th, 1641 patients were hospitalized, a new high during the period analyzed. Additionally, 333 COVID positive patients were in the ICU on July 6th the most recorded during the epidemic. Note: data is plotted on a log scale.

The data above show the number of deaths by day for Miami-Dade County starting on March 16th. N= the number of deaths by day.

Overall from March 16th to July 7th in Miami-Dade County, there has been a consistent linear decrease in the number of deaths per day. The peak number of deaths so far reported was 30 on April 27th. This decrease in deaths may be attributable to advances in COVID-19 treatments and standard of care. A decrease in median age of those impacted could also partially explain this decrease.

Conclusion

During the past two weeks, the number of positive COVID-19 tests obtained has increased by an average of 103 each day. Additionally, there has been a substantial increase in the proportion of positive COVID-19 tests obtained from about 5% in mid May when Miami-Dade reopened, to the current proportion of positive tests of over 20%. Furthermore, hospitalization census, ICU census, and ventilation census have all begun to increase over approximately the last three weeks. Hospitalization census hit a new high of 1641 on July 6th. Furthermore, the number of COVID-19 positive individuals in the ICU has reached a new high of 333 on July 6th, the last day analyzed. Over the period from June 27th to July 6th alone, the number of COVID-19 positive patients in the ICU increased by 61%. Additionally, the number of COVID-19 positive patients ventilated on July 6th was 171, the most since April 17th. This number may increase as ventilation tends to lag behind ICU admission. Taken together, this evidence points to increased community spread of COVID-19 in Miami-Dade County and represents a significant concern for the area. There have been substantial increases in the number of COVID-19 positive patients hospitalized, in intensive care, and on ventilators. This is a concern for hospital resource capacity.
